  "prompt": "What is one way slab and two way slab?",
  "response": "One-way and two-way slabs are different types of floor or roof systems used in building construction, distinguished by how they distribute loads.\n\nOne-Way Slab:\n- Spans in only one direction\n- Supported on two opposite sides\n- Reinforcement is primarily placed in the shorter direction\n- Load is transferred primarily in one direction\n- Typical span-to-depth ratio is 4 to 5\n- Common in rectangular rooms where one side is significantly longer\n- Examples: Rectangular rooms, corridors\n\nTwo-Way Slab:\n- Spans in both directions (length and width)\n- Supported on all four sides\n- Reinforcement is placed in both directions\n- Load is distributed equally in both directions\n- Typical span-to-depth ratio is 3 to 4\n- Common in square or nearly square rooms\n- More complex reinforcement pattern\n- Better load distribution\n\nKey differences:\n1. Direction of load transfer\n2. Reinforcement layout\n3. Structural behavior\n4. Typical application areas\n\nThe selection depends on room geometry, loading conditions, and structural requirements.",
